3e\u003cli\u003eSFPD currently has 12 human-controlled robots for purposes such as gaining situational awareness, diffusing potential bombs or helping in hostage negotiations. \u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003eThe Board of Supervisors\u0026#x27; Rules Committee, chaired by Aaron Peskin, recommended the ordinance for approval earlier this month.\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eYes, but: \u003c/strong\u003eHe told Axios, \u0026quot;This should not be construed as a green light to have robots wantonly kill people,\u0026quot; conceding they “could be misused.” \u003c/li\u003e\u003c/ul\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eWhat they\u0026#x27;re saying: \u003c/strong\u003eThe SFPD says it does not own or operate \u0026quot;robots outfitted with lethal force options,\u0026quot; and doesn\u0026#x27;t have any plans to augment with any \u0026quot;firearm,\u0026quot; Allison Maxie, a spokesperson with the SFPD, told Axios via email.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cul\u003e\u003cli\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eReality check: \u003c/strong\u003eIf the ordinance is fully approved, the SFPD would be authorized to equip existing robots with explosives \u0026quot;to breach fortified structures containing violent, armed, or dangerous subjects or used to contact, incapacitate, or disorient\u0026quot; a suspect who poses \u0026quot;a risk of loss of life to law enforcement or other first responders,\u0026quot; Maxie said.\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003eThe SFPD considers explosives \u0026quot;an intermediate force option,\u0026quot; but acknowledges they \u0026quot;could potentially cause injury or be fatal,\u0026quot; she said.\u003c/li\u003e\u003c/ul\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThe other side: \u003c/strong\u003eOutside of the public safety questions, there are racial and ethical implications for these new policing tools.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cul\u003e\u003cli\u003eYoel Haile, director of the criminal justice program at the American Civil Liberties Union of Northern California, does not think police departments should \u0026quot;have killer robots\u0026quot; in part because police \u003ca class=\"gtmContentClick\" data-vars-link-text=\"kill Black people at more than twice the rate of white people\" data-vars-click-url=\"https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/investigations/police-shootings-database/\" data-vars-content-id=\"1c38a30e-a3d5-4125-971c-3303071a2aed\" data-vars-headline=\"New ordinance lets police robots use lethal force\" data-vars-event-category=\"story\" data-vars-sub-category=\"story\" data-vars-item=\"in_content_link\" href=\"https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/investigations/police-shootings-database/\" target=\"_blank\"\u003ekill Black people at more than twice the rate of white people\u003c/a\u003e, per a Washington Post analysis. \u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003e\u0026quot;Remote-controlled killing machines will not make San Francisco safer,\u0026quot; Haile said. \u0026quot;This is a terrible idea.\u0026quot; \u003c/li\u003e\u003c/ul\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003ePreston, in a statement to Axios, \u003c/strong\u003esaid, \u0026quot;It is shocking that just two years after the nation collectively recognized that \u003ca class=\"gtmContentClick\" data-vars-link-text=\"police were using unjustified deadly force\" data-vars-click-url=\"https://www.axios.com/2021/12/11/race-in-america-slow-wheels-justice\" data-vars-content-id=\"1c38a30e-a3d5-4125-971c-3303071a2aed\" data-vars-headline=\"New ordinance lets police robots use lethal force\" data-vars-event-category=\"story\" data-vars-sub-category=\"story\" data-vars-item=\"in_content_link\" href=\"https://www.axios.com/2021/12/11/race-in-america-slow-wheels-justice\" target=\"_self\"\u003epolice were using unjustified deadly force\u003c/a\u003e against people, we are having a conversation about letting SFPD adopt a policy that would allow them to use robots to kill.\u0026quot;\u003c/p\u003e\u003cul\u003e\u003cli\u003eRonen said at yesterday\u0026#x27;s meeting that using robots for lethal force \u0026quot;creates this false distance that makes killing the individual easier.\u0026quot;\u003c/li\u003e\u003c/ul\u003e\u003cspan id=\"midStoryAd\" data-ad-status=\"AD\"\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eBy the numbers: \u003c/strong\u003eSFPD\u0026#x27;s \u003ca class=\"gtmContentClick\" data-vars-link-text=\"budget grew\" data-vars-click-url=\"https://www.sfchronicle.com/sf/article/S-F-supervisors-approve-14-billion-budget-that-17315801.php\" data-vars-content-id=\"1c38a30e-a3d5-4125-971c-3303071a2aed\" data-vars-headline=\"New ordinance lets police robots use lethal force\" data-vars-event-category=\"story\" data-vars-sub-category=\"story\" data-vars-item=\"in_content_link\" href=\"https://www.sfchronicle.com/sf/article/S-F-supervisors-approve-14-billion-budget-that-17315801.php\" target=\"_blank\"\u003ebudget grew\u003c/a\u003e to about $714 million for fiscal year 2023.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cul\u003e\u003cli\u003eThe department spent more than $10.5 million to acquire the robots and expects to spend about $1,445 per year to maintain the robots, \u003ca class=\"gtmContentClick\" data-vars-link-text=\"per the draft policy\" data-vars-click-url=\"https://sfgov.legistar.com/View.ashx?M=F\u0026amp;ID=11449771\u0026amp;GUID=9FC57C5A-6E68-4485-A989-632C3837B909\" data-vars-content-id=\"1c38a30e-a3d5-4125-971c-3303071a2aed\" data-vars-headline=\"New ordinance lets police robots use lethal force\" data-vars-event-category=\"story\" data-vars-sub-category=\"story\" data-vars-item=\"in_content_link\" href=\"https://sfgov.legistar.com/View.ashx?M=F\u0026amp;ID=11449771\u0026amp;GUID=9FC57C5A-6E68-4485-A989-632C3837B909\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eper the draft policy\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003eSFPD, however, may spend up to $10 million on the replacement of equipment without the approval of the Board of Supervisors.\u003c/li\u003e\u003c/ul\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eThe big picture: \u003c/strong\u003eThe idea of weaponized robots is controversial and sparks images of a more dystopian society.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cul\u003e\u003cli\u003eIn October, robot maker Boston Dynamics \u003ca class=\"gtmContentClick\" data-vars-link-text=\"signed an open letter\" data-vars-click-url=\"https://www.bostondynamics.com/open-letter-opposing-weaponization-general-purpose-robots\" data-vars-content-id=\"1c38a30e-a3d5-4125-971c-3303071a2aed\" data-vars-headline=\"New ordinance lets police robots use lethal force\" data-vars-event-category=\"story\" data-vars-sub-category=\"story\" data-vars-item=\"in_content_link\" href=\"https://www.bostondynamics.com/open-letter-opposing-weaponization-general-purpose-robots\" target=\"_blank\"\u003esigned an open letter\u003c/a\u003e alongside other firms \u003ca class=\"gtmContentClick\" data-vars-link-text=\"arguing the weaponization of robots\" data-vars-click-url=\"https://www.axios.com/2022/10/06/boston-dynamics-pledges-weaponize-robots\" data-vars-content-id=\"1c38a30e-a3d5-4125-971c-3303071a2aed\" data-vars-headline=\"New ordinance lets police robots use lethal force\" data-vars-event-category=\"story\" data-vars-sub-category=\"story\" data-vars-item=\"in_content_link\" href=\"https://www.axios.com/2022/10/06/boston-dynamics-pledges-weaponize-robots\" target=\"_self\"\u003earguing the weaponization of robots\u003c/a\u003e \u0026quot;raises new risks of harm and serious ethical issues.\u0026quot;\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003eOne ethical issue: who is at fault if a robot accidentally kills someone?\u003c/li\u003e\u003cli\u003eThe Electronic Frontier Foundation \u003ca class=\"gtmContentClick\" data-vars-link-text=\"argues\" data-vars-click-url=\"https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2021/07/dont-let-police-arm-autonomous-or-remote-controlled-robots-and-drones\" data-vars-content-id=\"1c38a30e-a3d5-4125-971c-3303071a2aed\" data-vars-headline=\"New ordinance lets police robots use lethal force\" data-vars-event-category=\"story\" data-vars-sub-category=\"story\" data-va